SIMPLE: scurrility
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scurrility
<hw>Scur*ril"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>scurrilitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>scurrilit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being scurrile or scurrilous;
mean, vile, or obscene jocularity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your reasons . . . have been sharp and sententious, pleasant
without <qex>scurrility</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is scurrile or scurrilous; gross or
obscene language; low buffoonery; vulgar abuse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Interrupting prayers and sermons with clamor and
<qex>scurrility</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Scurrilousness; abuse; insolence; vulgarity;
indecency.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scurrilous</ent>⟦br⟧
